The paper deals with improving the search efficiency of constraint satisfaction problems (CSPs) by using both semantic and structural properties of the constraint network. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category, which deals with intelligent agents, reasoning, and problem-solving. Additionally, the paper introduces a new local consistency method called pivot consistency, which could fall under the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The paper also presents associated properties, which could be relevant to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category, which deals with algorithms that can learn from and make predictions on data. Furthermore, the paper deals with decomposing CSPs, which could be relevant to the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) sub-category, which deals with mathematical structures and their applications. Finally, the paper deals with improving search efficiency, which could be relevant to the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category, which deals with the study of the inherent difficulty of computational problems.
